"name":"Saxby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","nickname, perhaps for someone quick to take offense and draw his sword, or for an instructor in swordsmanship, from Middle English <i>sakespey</i> ‘draw sword’ (Old French <i>sacquespee</i>, from <i>sacque(r)</i> ‘to draw, extract’ + <i>espee</i> ‘sword’).","habitational name from either of two places called Saxby (Leicestershire, Lincolnshire). The Lincolnshire placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Saxi</i> (see   Sax   3) + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’, while the Leicestershire placename may arise from Old English <i>Seaxe</i> ‘the Saxons’ (genitive plural <i>Seaxna</i>) + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i>, or may have the same etymology as the Lincolnshire placename."],"variants":[{"name":"Sax","meanings":["South German: variant of   Sachs   1.","Flemish and Dutch: variant of   Sas   2.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Saxe</i> (Old Norse <i>Saxi</i>, derived from <i>sax</i> ‘one-edged sword’)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Alice Saxby had at least 1 son with Thomas Saxb